To convert the solid RHAs into water-soluble sodium silicate 5 g of RHAs, collected after calcination, was refluxed with 100 mL 2.5 M NaOH at 90°C for 2 h under continuous vigorous stirring. The resultant slurry was filtered and washed with water to remove insoluble char and impurities. The transparent filtrate of sodium silicate solution was allowed to cool before being titrated with 1 M HCl under vigorous stirring to precipitate silica. After neutralization, the solution was set aside for 48 h to allow the growth of silica gel. The formed gel was dialyzed against distilled water through cellulose filtration membrane to remove soluble sodium chloride salt until the conductivity of wash solution was below 200 S/m. The clean silica gel was lyophilized overnight to get rid of water. The freeze-dried product was stored in a vacuum desiccator for further characterizations. The amount of organic maters in the differently prepared samples was estimated from the loss on ignition (LOI) % value that was calculated via Eq. (1)1LOI%=(mb-ma)×100/mb\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
